# =============================================================================
# update.sh configuration   (example / template)
# =============================================================================
#
# This file is sourced by update.sh as ROOT (the script self-elevates), so it
# is plain bash: you may use variables, arrays, and comments. Keep it simple --
# assignments only, no commands. update.sh refuses to source this file if it is
# world-writable or not owned by you/root (see the safety gate in the script).
#
# Live location (auto-created from this template on first run):
#     ~/.config/update.sh/config
# Override per-run with:  update.sh --config /path/to/config
# Skip entirely with:     update.sh --no-config
# See the merged, effective settings with:  update.sh --print-config
#
# Precedence (lowest to highest):
#     built-in defaults  <  this config file  <  command-line flags
#
# Every setting below is OPTIONAL. Anything you leave commented out keeps the
# script's built-in default. The values shown are those built-in defaults.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. DEFAULT BEHAVIOR
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# DEFAULT_ACTIONS -- which checks run when you invoke update.sh with NO action
# flags (e.g. just `update.sh`, or `update.sh -P` with only a modifier).
# Order here does not matter; the script always runs them in its fixed order.
# Valid tokens: clean orphans update rebuilds python-rebuild pacnew firmware
#               kernel aur-audit aur-scan all
# Note: `kernel`, `aur-audit`, and `aur-scan` are intentionally NOT in the
# default set upstream (kernel is interactive; the AUR security checks are
# explicit-only). You can add them here if you want them every run.
#DEFAULT_ACTIONS=(clean orphans update rebuilds python-rebuild pacnew firmware)

# UPDATER -- which backend `-u/--update` uses by default:
#   yay    = official repos via pacman + AUR via yay, with PKGBUILD review (default)
#   pacman = official repos only, no AUR
#   pamac  = repos + AUR via pamac (the old default)
# Overridden on the command line by -Y / -P / -m.
#UPDATER="yay"

# AUTO_REBUILD -- if true, the rebuild checks (-r and -y) will offer to rebuild
# the affected packages (after a confirmation prompt) instead of only listing
# them. Overridden on the command line by -R/--auto-rebuild.
#AUTO_REBUILD=false

# AUR_RECENT_DAYS -- in the AUR audit (-A), a package whose PKGBUILD changed
# within this many days is tagged RECENTLY-CHANGED (a "give it a look" signal,
# not a verdict). Lower = noisier/more cautious.
#AUR_RECENT_DAYS=21

# AUR_IOC_CAMPAIGNS -- which threat-intel campaigns from lenucksi/aur-malware-check
# the audit (-A) and scan (-S) pull live IOC lists from. Remove ones you do not
# care about, or add new campaign directory names as they are published.
#AUR_IOC_CAMPAIGNS=(aur-infected chaos-rat russian-spam)


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2. EXCLUSIONS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# All three lists accept EXACT package names and shell GLOBS, e.g.:
#     "mailspring"      -> exact match
#     "python-*"        -> every package starting with python-
#     "*-git"           -> every -git package
# Matching is case-sensitive (package names are lowercase by convention).

# EXCLUDE_ALIEN -- foreign/AUR packages to SUPPRESS from the noise of the
# foreign-package report (alien-pkgs.txt) and the AUR audit/scan output. Use
# this for packages you have already vetted and do not want to keep re-reading.
# The script prints how many entries it suppressed so nothing is hidden silently.
# Example:
#EXCLUDE_ALIEN=(brave-bin google-chrome visual-studio-code-bin)

# KEEP_ORPHANS -- orphaned packages that should NEVER be offered for removal by
# `-o/--orphans`. Use this to protect intentionally-installed leaf packages that
# nothing depends on (so they look like orphans but you want to keep them).
# Everything NOT matched here is listed and you are prompted before each removal.
# Example:
#KEEP_ORPHANS=(downgrade nvchecker python-pipx)

# LUA_ALLOWLIST -- packages allowlisted in the advisory yay PKGBUILD tripwire
# (the AURPreInstall hook). Listed packages are skipped by the hook's
# supply-chain pattern scan, suppressing its warnings for software you trust to
# legitimately use Node/Electron/JS build tooling. update.sh writes this list to
# ~/.config/yay/allowlist.txt, which the hook reads at install time -- this file
# is the single source of truth (do not hand-edit allowlist.txt).
# Globs are honored here too (e.g. "*-electron").
#LUA_ALLOWLIST=(mailspring)
